China may emerge as Australia's largest beef export market.
China faces a severe shortage of pork after the outbreak of African swine fever and is expected to become Australia's largest beef export market, said an animal protein analyst at Rabobank.
After the outbreak, which has led authorities to incinerate the corpses of pigs, Chinese consumers are switching from pork to other animal protein, and in the past year, the number of live pigs in China has halved while the pork price has almost doubled.
China produces and consumes 2/3 of the world's pork.
Chenjun Pan, a senior animal protein analyst at Rabobank China, said that China’s demand for other meats, including beef, has increased; China, the world's largest importer of animal protein, currently accounts for 27% of the world's pork imports and 24% of the world's beef imports.
China's beef imports from Australia increased by 65% in the first half of this year, and China overtook the United States and Japan to become Australia's largest beef importer, said Ms. Pan.
The Chinese government said yesterday that it would release more pork from emergency reserves before celebrating the 70th anniversary of the Communist Party of China.
